{
  "doc_id": "47668",
  "text": "It is reported that knotting of the tube occurs during insertion and that the traction during retrieval tightens the knot. Our case supports this theory because the tube continued to function while it was in situ. The resistance experienced during the removal of the tube increases progressively as the catheter passes through the narrowest part of the esophagus. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Egan et al. [CITATION_3] reported a similar case where upon attempting to remove the tube, the patient experienced severe pain and developed epistaxis. In their example, the ENT surgeon was able to advance the NGT, cut the external distal portion and retrieve the remainder through the oropharynx.",
